es, Laurent.","French and Walloon: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, from Old French <i>fontaine</i>, from Late Latin <i>fontana</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>fons</i> (see   Font  ); or a habitational name from Fontaine, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Fountaine  .","Shortened form of French   Lafontaine  , a variant of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Fontenot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Ulysse, Andrus, Alcide, Andre, Edouard, Lucien, Marise, Monique, Remy.","French: variant of <b>Fonteneau</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from any of several places mainly in the westcentral part of France so named. The surname <i>Fontenot</i> is very rare in France.","History: Jean-Louis Fonteneau/Fontenot from Montierneuf in Vienne, France, married Louise-Angélique Henry in Mobile, AL, in 1726."]},{"name":"Fontenelle","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from (La) Fontenelle, the name of several places in various parts of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fontenette","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from Fontenette, the name of several places mainly in the central part of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fountain","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from one or more of the places in France named Fontaine, Fonteyne, or Lafontaine (see   Fontaine  ).","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or well, from Middle English <i>fontayne</i> (Old French <i>fontaine</i>) ‘spring, fountain’, sometimes with a plural <i>-s</i>, and synonymous with   Well  , of which <i>Fountain(es)</i> may sometimes have been a translation."]},{"name":"Font","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Luis, Miguel, Rafael, Eduardo, Raul, Eugenio, Pedro, Roberto, Aida.","Catalan and southern French: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, Catalan and Occitan <i>font</i> ‘spring, well’ (from Latin <i>fons</i>, genitive <i>fontis</i>).","English: variant of   Fant  ."]},{"name":"Fontan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Angel, Benigno, Carlos, Jose, Juana, Manuel, Pedro, Adolfo, Aida, Alfredo, Candido, Emilia.","Spanish and Galician (<b>Fontán</b>): habitational name from any of the many places called Fontán, from <i>fontán</i> ‘spring’.","French: variant of   Fontaine  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mahaut de Fontaine was born in 1109, in Conde-sur-Ifs, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France as the daughter of Wauthier II de Fontaine-l'Evêque and Marie de Zottegem. She had at least 1 son with Wedric de Condé."},"et":{"1109–":"1109–Surnud","1100–1144":"1100–1144","1109–Female":"1109–Surnud","1112–1183":"1112–1183","1104–1169":"1104–1169","1130–1218":"1130–1218","1085–Male":"1085–Surnud","–1144":"–1144","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1112":"1112","1144":"1144","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1183":"1183","1109":"1109","about 1130":"umbes 1130","1218":"1218","Conde, Calvados, France":"Conde-sur-Ifs, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Roman Empire":"Roman Empire"},"fi":{"1109–":"1109–Kuollut","1100–1144":"1100–1144","1109–Female":"1109–Kuollut","1112–1183":"1112–1183","1104–1169":"1104–1169","1130–1218":"1130–1218","1085–Male":"1085